06_big_data_analysis


  1. Question

    S-ID.A: Summarize, represent, and interpret data on a single count or measurement variable. Use calculators, spreadsheets, and other technology as appropriate.

    A spinner was made to model a discrete-uniform distribution.


    The spinner was spun many times, producing the values below.

    x
    5 24 8 17 20 29 16 15
    2 2 22 28 28 2 26 3
    21 30 13 13 28 6 5 16
    5 26 6 22 12 19 31 16
    12 13 19 26 3 29 24 24
    3 16 16 2 4 16 21 4
    26 7 27 15 15 20 3 4
    18 16 12 4 14 4 26 26
    14 27 30 12 26 26 23 20
    13 17 10 5 13 21 4 5
    31 11 30 23 3 21 23 1
    23 31 1 6 14 14 17 15
    15 9 6 19 15 23 22 5


    Please help describe the values by finding a few statistics.

    The sample size, \(n\)

    The sample size is simply a count of how many values are in the sample.

    • \(n=\)

    The sample total, \(\sum x\)

    The sample total is found by adding up all the values. Informally, we write it as \(\sum x\). More formally, we write it as \(\sum\limits_{i=1}^n x_i\). Notice, both methods refer to the summation operator.

    • \(\sum x =\)

    The sample mean, \(\bar{x}\)

    The sample mean, or in common parlance the sample average, is found by dividing the sample total by the sample size. The symbol \(\bar{x}\) is pronounced x bar. Please round to the nearest tenth. \[\bar{x} = \frac{\sum x}{n}\]

    • \(\bar{x}=\)

    The sample median

    The median represents a boundary between the lower half of the values and the upper half of the values. This should be review. Remember, it helps to sort the data. We could write a formula using a sort function and floor and ceiling functions:

    \[\mathrm{median}(x) ~=~ \frac{\mathrm{sort}(x)_{\lceil n/2\rceil}+\mathrm{sort}(x)_{\lfloor n/2+1\rfloor}}{2}\]

    But, youll probably just want to sort the values. Then, if the sample size is odd, find the middle value. If the sample size is even, find the mean of the two middle values.

    • \(\mathrm{median}(x) =\)

    A conditional count

    In data analysis, we often use conditional counts. In this case, I want you to count how many values are less than 22. I am using the # symbol to represent a count, and in the parentheses I am denoting a condition (with an inequality).

    • \(\#(x < 22) =\)

    A sample proportion

    What proportion of the values are greater than 21? A proportion is a conditional count divided by the sample size. Please round to the nearest hundredth.

    • \(\mathrm{proportion(x> 21)}= \frac{\#(x> 21)}{n} =\)


    Solution

    \[n=104\] \[\sum x=1629\] \[\bar{x}=15.7\] \[\mathrm{median}(x)=16\] \[\#(x < 22) = 72\] \[\mathrm{proportion}(x > 21)=0.31\]

    I recommend doing this with a spreadsheet. First paste the values into a new sheet. You might need to hit ctrl + shift + v instead of just ctrl + v.

    Then use the functions shown here:
